NAME
    App::PathNaiveUtils - Utilities related to Path::Naive

VERSION
    This document describes version 0.001 of App::PathNaiveUtils (from Perl
    distribution App-PathNaiveUtils), released on 2020-02-12.

DESCRIPTION
    This distributions provides the following command-line utilities:

    *   pn-abs-path

    *   pn-concat-and-normalize-path

    *   pn-concat-path

    *   pn-is-abs-path

    *   pn-normalize-path

    *   pn-split-path

FUNCTIONS
  abs_path
    Usage:

     abs_path($path, $basepath) -> any

    This function is not exported.

    Arguments ('*' denotes required arguments):

    *   $basepath* => *pathname::unix*

    *   $path* => *pathname::unix*

    Return value: (any)

  concat_and_normalize_path
    Usage:

     concat_and_normalize_path($paths, ...) -> any

    This function is not exported.

    Arguments ('*' denotes required arguments):

    *   $paths* => *array[pathname::unix]*

    Return value: (any)

  concat_path
    Usage:

     concat_path($paths, ...) -> any

    This function is not exported.

    Arguments ('*' denotes required arguments):

    *   $paths* => *array[pathname::unix]*

    Return value: (any)

  is_abs_path
    Usage:

     is_abs_path(%args) -> [status, msg, payload, meta]

    This function is not exported.

    Arguments ('*' denotes required arguments):

    *   path* => *pathname::unix*

    *   quiet => *true*

    Returns an enveloped result (an array).

    First element (status) is an integer containing HTTP status code (200
    means OK, 4xx caller error, 5xx function error). Second element (msg) is
    a string containing error message, or 'OK' if status is 200. Third
    element (payload) is optional, the actual result. Fourth element (meta)
    is called result metadata and is optional, a hash that contains extra
    information.

    Return value: (any)

  normalize_path
    Usage:

     normalize_path($path) -> any

    This function is not exported.

    Arguments ('*' denotes required arguments):

    *   $path* => *pathname::unix*

    Return value: (any)

  split_path
    Usage:

     split_path($path) -> any

    This function is not exported.

    Arguments ('*' denotes required arguments):

    *   $path* => *pathname::unix*

    Return value: (any)

